To determine how long it takes Janice and Jennie to collectively bike 1 mile, we first calculate their combined speed. Janice bikes at 10 mph, and Jennie at 20 mph, so their combined speed is \(10 + 20 = 30\) mph. 

The time \(t\) (in hours) required to cover 1 mile together is given by:
\[
\text{Time} = \frac{\text{Total Distance}}{\text{Combined Speed}} = \frac{1 \text{ mile}}{30 \text{ mph}} = \frac{1}{30} \text{ hours}.
\]

Converting \(\frac{1}{30}\) hours to minutes:
\[
\frac{1}{30} \times 60 \text{ minutes} = 2 \text{ minutes}.
\]

Verification: In 2 minutes (\(\frac{1}{30}\) hours), Janice bikes \(10 \times \frac{1}{30} = \frac{1}{3}\) mile, and Jennie bikes \(20 \times \frac{1}{30} = \frac{2}{3}\) mile. Their combined distance is \(\frac{1}{3} + \frac{2}{3} = 1\) mile, confirming the solution.

Answer: B) 2 minutes.

\[
\frac{1}{30} \times 60 = 2 \text{ minutes}.
\]
